If you don't know Mike Leigh then you haven't been watching too many British films. If there is a British filmmaker that you have a knackering to see, then I suggest you watch Mike Leigh. His Secrets & Lies made a splash at the Oscars more than a decade ago when it was nominated for five Academy Awards.

I was just a mere lad when Secrets & Lies debuted and I didn't quite grasp the concept of it....so, I wrote it off. What a stupid kid I was back then. Mike Leigh has to be the absolute master of everyday human functionality. He is just so perfect with words that I would look like an inarticulate gutter baby next to him.

Another Year takes place over four seasons within the course of a year -- we get to follow an extreme happily married couple with very unfortunate names, Tom & Gerri (Broadbent & Sheen, respectively). Gerri has a friend from work named Mary (Manville, who should have been nominated last year, hands down) who is, to say the least, envies the women from TV's Desperate Housewives. Tom and Gerri have a son, Joe (Maltman), who coyly rejects the advances of said desperate housewife while also trying to be the utmost proper gentlemen he can be. It's not like Mary is devoid of men of any kind -- she very rudely denies the advances of Tom & Gerri's friend, Ken (Wight), who would probably treat her like a princess.

I know that it may seem long at 124 minutes (5 minutes is credits) but I wanted more. I wanted to see how everything turned out.... but.... I understand the film and why it ended where it did. So often do we get a picture that shows us the life of regular, ordinary people. That's what this film is all about. It's one year out of the life of normal, regular people. There are no superpowers, no villains, no evil corporation or pirates to defeat. No hidden pregnancies, deceit and who slept with whom nonsense. This is real life. Please keep in mind, that this is not a mystery picture or brain-teasing thriller... this is a character study/piece that will engage you with it's characters, make you chuckle a bit with the often subtle humor that is life and maybe even put you in a 'what if that happened to me...' sort of mentality. More reviews at www.soveryterry.com Final Grade: B+
