They are quite rare, the movies in which no shot is fired, no crime is solved and no car is chased. Another year is such a movie. It is a movie without spectacular twists or beautiful locations, but with people and events that could be real. It's about friendship, desperation, love, disappointment, hope. That's why I really enjoyed this movie.

Mike Leigh is a specialist of such slice-of-life movies. In this film, he shows us the day-to-day life of a happy loving couple and their not so happy friends and family. The acting is absolutely outstanding, with Lesley Manville in the role of her life. If anyone deserves an Oscar, she does.

But then again, you could call this a boring movie. My movie-going companion did. His point is: if he wants to see real life, he can look around him all day. That's not what he's going to the cinema for.

In a way, he is right. Cinema is about seeing things you don't see in real life. Famous stars, suspense stories that make you wonder whodunit, comedy which makes you laugh, intelligent plots and sudden twists, or even a new insight in a historic event. Wasn't it Hitchcock who said that he left everything ordinary out of the film?
